Multivariate Regression Examples

Examples of regression models with more than one variable

Swiss data

Scatterplots showing pairwise relationships between the variables.

All of the variables, except for fertility, are proportions of population.

all <- lm(Fertility ~ ., swiss)
summary(all)

Call:
lm(formula = Fertility ~ ., data = swiss)

For every 1% increase in percent of males involved in agriculture as an occupation we expect a .17 decrease in fertility, holding all the other variables constant; for every 1% increase in Catholicism, we expect a .10 increase in fertility, holding all other variables constant.

The * at the far end of the row indicates that the influence of Agriculture on Fertility is significant.

summary(lm(Fertility ~ Agriculture, swiss))

The sign of the Agriculture coefficient changed form negative (when all the variables were included in the model) to positive (only using Agriculture).

The presence of the other factorsffects the influence of Agriculture has on fertility.

Education and performance on Examination are expected to be correlated

cor(swiss$Education, swiss$Examination)
[1] 0.6984153
cor(swiss$Education, swiss$Agriculture)
[1] -0.6395225

Negative correlation. This negative correlation might be affecting Agriculture’s influence on Fertility.

Generate 5 lm.

Each model has one more independent variable than the preceding model, so the first has just one independent variable, Agriculture, and the last has all 5.

makelms()
Agriculture Agriculture Agriculture Agriculture Agriculture 
  0.1942017   0.1095281  -0.2030377  -0.2206455  -0.1721140

The addition of Education changes the sign of the Agriculture’s coefficient from positive to negative

Adding a variable that will provide no new linear info to the model.

Adding this new variable will not change the model.

# new variable
ec <- swiss$Examination + swiss$Catholic

# new model
efit <- lm(Fertility ~ . + ec, swiss)

# subtract efit coefficients from the frist model all
efit$coef - all$coef
     (Intercept)      Agriculture      Examination        Education         Catholic 
               0                0                0                0                0 
Infant.Mortality               ec 
               0               NA 
all$coefficients-efit$coefficients
     (Intercept)      Agriculture      Examination        Education         Catholic 
               0                0                0                0                0

               0               NA
